ngland, the causes and results of the increasing baronial fear of the king, the "managerial revolution" of the English church, and the effect of the ius commune on English common law. They also examine the burgeoning economy of the early thirteenth century and its effect on English towns, the background to discontent over the royal forests which eventually led to the Charter of the Forest, the effect of Magna Carta on widows and property, and the course of criminal justice before 1215. The volume concludes with the first critical edition of an open letter from King John explaining his position in the matter ofWilliam de Briouze. Contributors: Janet S. Loengard, Ralph V. Turner, John Gillingham, David Crouch, David Crook, James A. Brundage, John Hudson, Barbara Hanawalt, James Masschaele  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLawzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAngevin rulers.  aBaronial fear.  aCharter of the Forest.  aConstitutional history.  aCriminal justice.  aEarly thirteenth century.  aEnglish church.  aIus commune.  aKing John.  aMagna Carta.  aMonarch and subject.  aOpen letter.  aPolitical history.  aRoyal forests.  aWidows.  aWilliam de Briouze.1 aBrundage, James A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrundage, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrook, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrouch, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillingham, John B, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillingham, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanawalt, Barbara A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/